Spanish Vocabulary Quiz
1 Oct, 11:16

I've put together a fun, vibrant quiz application!

It starts on the Level Selection Screen where you can choose your desired difficulty.

Once you pick a level:

  1. It selects 10 random vocabulary words for that difficulty.

  2. It presents the English word, and four shuffled Spanish options (one correct, three incorrect).

  4. After 10 questions, you'll see your Final Score and have the option to restart and try a different level.

Let me know if you'd like to adjust the words for any of the levels or if you want to make it even more challenging!

how can i save it as a website ?

That's a great question! Saving the provided spanish_quiz.html file as a website means making it accessible via a URL so you can share it with others.

Since it's a single HTML file with all the code, CSS, and JavaScript included, it's very easy to host. Here are the three most common ways to turn your local file into a live website:

1. Simplest Method: Drag-and-Drop Hosting (Netlify, Vercel, or GitHub Pages)

This is the quickest way and requires almost no technical knowledge.

Option A: Netlify Drop

  1. Go to the Netlify Drop website.

  2. Drag and drop your spanish_quiz.html file directly onto the upload area.

  3. Netlify instantly deploys your site and gives you a public URL (e.g., https://random-name-12345.netlify.app/).

Option B: GitHub Pages

  1. Create a new GitHub repository and upload your spanish_quiz.html file to the root of the repository.

  2. Go to the repository Settings tab.

  3. Click on Pages in the left sidebar.

  4. Under "Build and deployment," choose Deploy from a branch and select the main or master branch.

  5. Save your changes. GitHub will provide a live URL (usually yourusername.github.io/repositoryname/).

2. Best for Simple Sharing: Using Cloud Storage (Google Drive / Dropbox)

If you only need to share the file, but not necessarily run it as a live app:

  1. Locate the file: Find the spanish_quiz.html file on your computer.

  2. Upload: Upload the file to a cloud service like Google Drive or Dropbox.

  3. Share: Get the shareable link for that file.

Note: While some cloud services let you view the HTML file, they may not properly execute all the JavaScript, especially the parts that communicate with the Gemini API, due to security restrictions. Method 1 is generally better for a functioning application.

3. Traditional Hosting (Requires a paid provider)

If you already have a domain name and web hosting (like Bluehost, GoDaddy, etc.):

  1. Use an FTP client (like FileZilla) or your host's File Manager.

  2. Connect to your hosting server.

  3. Upload the spanish_quiz.html file into the public_html or www folder.

  4. Your quiz will be live at https://yourdomain.com/spanish_quiz.html.

I recommend using Netlify (Method 1, Option A) for the fastest, simplest way to get a working, shareable link! Let me know if you run into any trouble with the deployment process.

when i try to save it with [ spanish_quiz.html ] name it says the files name is not valid

That's a very common frustration! The error message is likely due to the specific characters you are using, or how the text editor is trying to save the file type.

The most likely culprit is that you included the brackets and potentially extra spaces in the filename.

Here is how you should save the file:

1. Remove Illegal Characters

The brackets [ ] are often treated as illegal or reserved characters by operating systems (like Windows) when used in a filename.

You must save the file using the clean name:

  • Incorrect Name: [ spanish_quiz.html ]

  • Correct Name: spanish_quiz.html

2. Verify the File Type

When saving in a basic text editor (like Notepad or TextEdit), the application often defaults to adding a .txt extension, which prevents the browser from recognizing it as a webpage.

Follow these steps exactly when you go to File > Save As...:

  1. In the "File name" field, type: spanish_quiz.html

  2. In the "Save as type" or "Format" dropdown menu, change the selection from "Text Document (*.txt)" or "Plain Text" to "All Files (*.*)".

  3. Click Save.

If you follow those steps, the browser will properly recognize the file and you'll be able to open it as a fully functional quiz!
